291
0:37:19,6 --> 0:37:29,11
In time, as the warm waters of El Ni–o fade,
the productivity of the Sea of Cortez begins


292
0:37:29,11 --> 0:37:39,39
to rise again.


293
0:37:39,39 --> 0:37:46,1
With the return of La Ni–a, the wind blows
again across the barren shorelines.


294
0:37:46,1 --> 0:38:1,63
Cold water rises up from the deep, laden with
nutrients, and the sea grows cloudy with plankton.


295
0:38:1,63 --> 0:38:7,31
Life returns with a flourish.


296
0:38:7,31 --> 0:38:13,26
John Steinbeck and Ed Ricketts celebrated
the rush of living organisms.


297
0:38:13,26 --> 0:38:19,47
"The sea here swarms with life," they wrote.


298
0:38:19,47 --> 0:38:24,55
"We could see the splashing of great schools
